org.gradoop.temporal.model.api

Interface TemporalGraphOperators

  • All Known Implementing Classes:
    TemporalGraph

    public interface TemporalGraphOperators
    Defines the operators that are available on a TemporalGraph.

      • diff

        TemporalGraph diff(TemporalPredicate firstSnapshot,
                   TemporalPredicate secondSnapshot)
        Compares two snapshots of this graph. Given two temporal predicates, this operation will check if a graph element (vertex or edge) was added, removed or persists in the second snapshot compared to the first snapshot. This operation returns the union of both snapshots with the following changes: A property with key will be set on each graph element. Its value will be set to
        • 0, if the element is present in both snapshots.
        • 1, if the element is present in the second, but not the first snapshot (i.e. it was added since the first snapshot).
        • -1, if the element is present in the first, but not the second snapshot (i.e. it was removed since the first snapshot).
        Graph elements present in neither snapshot will be discarded. The resulting graph will not be verified, i.e. dangling edges could occur. Use the verify() operator to validate the graph. The graph head is preserved.
        Parameters:
        firstSnapshot - The predicate used to determine the first snapshot.
        secondSnapshot - The predicate used to determine the second snapshot.
        Returns:
        A logical graph containing the union of vertex and edge sets of both snapshots, defined by the given two predicate functions. A property with key Diff.PROPERTY_KEY is set on each graph element with a numerical value (-1, 0, 1) defined above.

      • query

        default TemporalGraphCollection query(String query)
        Evaluates the given query using the Cypher query engine. The engine uses default morphism strategies, which is vertex homomorphism and edge isomorphism. The vertex and edge data of the data graph elements is attached to the resulting vertices. Note, that this method used no statistics about the data graph which may result in bad runtime performance. Use query(String, GraphStatistics) to provide statistics for the query planner.
        Parameters:
        query - Cypher query
        Returns:
        graph collection containing matching subgraphs

      • query

        default TemporalGraphCollection query(String query,
                                      String constructionPattern)
        Evaluates the given query using the Cypher query engine. The engine uses default morphism strategies, which is vertex homomorphism and edge isomorphism. The vertex and edge data of the data graph elements is attached to the resulting vertices.

        Note, that this method used no statistics about the data graph which may result in bad runtime performance. Use query(String, GraphStatistics) to provide statistics for the query planner.

        In addition, the operator can be supplied with a construction pattern allowing the creation of new graph elements based on variable bindings of the match pattern. Consider the following example:
        graph.query( "MATCH (a:Author)-[:WROTE]->(:Paper)<-[:WROTE]-(b:Author) WHERE a <> b", "(a)-[:CO_AUTHOR]->(b)")

        The query pattern is looking for pairs of authors that worked on the same paper. The construction pattern defines a new edge of type CO_AUTHOR between the two entities.

        Parameters:
        query - Cypher query string
        constructionPattern - Construction pattern
        Returns:
        graph collection containing the output of the construct pattern

        TemporalGraphCollection query(String query,
                              String constructionPattern,
                              GraphStatistics graphStatistics)
        Evaluates the given query using the Cypher query engine. The engine uses default morphism strategies, which is vertex homomorphism and edge isomorphism. The vertex and edge data of the data graph elements is attached to the resulting vertices.

        In addition, the operator can be supplied with a construction pattern allowing the creation of new graph elements based on variable bindings of the match pattern. Consider the following example:
        graph.query( "MATCH (a:Author)-[:WROTE]->(:Paper)<-[:WROTE]-(b:Author) WHERE a <> b", "(a)-[:CO_AUTHOR]->(b)")

        The query pattern is looking for pairs of authors that worked on the same paper. The construction pattern defines a new edge of type CO_AUTHOR between the two entities.

        Parameters:

        constructionPattern - Construction pattern
        graphStatistics - statistics about the data graph
